In the bustling Floating Market of Aethria, a revered ledger keeper is tasked with maintaining the record of traded goods that continuously flow through the market’s wooden pathways. Each good is marked by its unique token number, and the ledger begins empty, awaiting the day’s collection. The keeper faces the challenge of handling a vast number of transactions — possibly up to five hundred thousand — as merchants frequently add goods to the line of wares or, sometimes, opt to replace all items of one kind with another across the entire ledger. This grand ledger serves not just as a record but as the pulse of the market’s ever-changing commerce.

The market’s rules are both straightforward and strict. On each turn, a single event occurs, and it comes in one of two ways. Either a merchant introduces a new commodity token, appending it to the end of the ledger’s list, thus adding one more entry to the growing chain of goods. Or, a merchant requests a transformation: wherever an old token appears in the ledger, it must be replaced everywhere with a new token, no exceptions. This means the entire ledger’s history can morph, reflecting the new preferred token instead of the old one. The tokens’ values can be as small as one and can climb as high as half a million, preserving uniqueness and order among the goods. The ledger must track each change with utmost precision.

The keeper’s task is to process these transactions in order, maintaining the ledger so that after the final event, the ledger reflects all additions and replacements in perfect sequence. The goal is to produce the final, unbroken sequence of tokens—the exact market inventory—at day’s end. Efficiency is essential, as the ledger may swell to vast sizes, and replacements are sweeping and instantaneous. The keeper’s output should be a single line listing the tokens in order, reflecting how the goods lie after every transaction has been applied.

To illustrate, consider a day with seven transactions. The first merchant places token three in the ledger, starting the stock. Then, a token one is added, followed by a market decree that every token one should now be regarded as token two. The ledger grows with token two and token one additions, but before the day ends, all tokens one become token three. These chain changes leave the ledger transformed, showing the final ordered inventory as: three, two, two, three, two.

On a simpler day, four transactions serve as another example: tokens one, two, and one again are placed, followed by an order that tokens two should be replaced by token two — a command causing no real change. The ledger thus remains with tokens one, two, one at its close.

One last day displays the complexity with eight events, starting not with additions, but a command to replace token one with four, which makes no change as the ledger is empty. Tokens one, four, and two are added, followed by modifications replacing twos with fours, then all fours turn to three, and another token two enters next. A final replacement turns all twos into sevens, resulting in the final ledger: one, three, three, seven.

Through every twist and turn of tokens being added and transformed, the floating market ledger faithfully tells the tale of goods traded, ensuring that every merchant’s transaction leaves a clear, unbroken record—ready for the market’s next lively day.

In the ancient Arcane Academy, there lies a profound test known only to the most adept mathematicians of the realm—a challenge woven into the tapestry of spatial magic and reflection. Imagine a grand plane, a mystical tableau, upon which certain sacred points are inscribed, each bearing coordinates composed of whole, unfragmented integers. Among these points, one is special and known as the origin marker, a starting beacon named M0. Alongside it, there are a sequence of enchanted anchors, known simply as the A-points, numbered from the first all the way to the last, their count always an odd number, but not too vast—never surpassing a hundred thousand in quantity. Each sacred point from the origin and the anchors never strays beyond a thousand steps in any direction, a boundary set by the Academy’s ancient runes.

The test unfolds by generating an infinite sequence of magical markers, labelled M1, M2, and onwards, each born from the previous through a secret operation dictated by the A-points in a circular ritual. Specifically, to find the next marker, one must locate the anchor point chosen by cycling through the A-list in order—wrapping back to the start after the last—and perform the sacred art of reflection centered upon this anchor. This means that each new marker is positioned symmetrically opposite to the previous marker with respect to the current anchor, as if a mirror set in that anchor casts the past point back into the magical expanse at a new location. This repeating dance continues infinitely, and the sorcerers seek to know the exact location of the marker bearing a particular index, far along this endless mirror-chain, designated by a number called j—which can be as large as a quintillion or more, a challenge not only of magic but of patience and wit.

Your quest, as a candidate of the Academy, is to discern the precise coordinates of the marker Mj. Before the ceremony begins, you will be presented with the number of anchors, always odd and within a hundred thousand, and the mystical index j—telling you which marker's coordinates you must unveil. On the next line, the coordinates of the origin beacon M0 will be revealed. Then, you will receive line after line, one for each anchor point, detailing their robust integer coordinates on this magical plane. You must use these inputs and wield the powers of symmetry and sequence wisely to conjure the coordinates of the j-th marker, revealing its location on a single line—two numbers standing side by side, telling the story of its position.

Let us consider the tales of challengers past: In one trial, three anchors set the stage and the task was to find the fourth marker beyond the origin. Beginning at the heart (0, 0), with anchors at (1,1), (2,3), and (-5,3), the sorcerers found the elusive marker dwelling at (14, 0). Another seeker, facing the identical three anchors but starting at (5, 5), sought only the first mirror beyond the origin, discovering a point at (1995, 1995), a grand leap reflecting the anchor's potent sway.

Thus, through the infinite weave of mirror-like symmetries, your challenge is cut clear: to grasp the location of the j-th M-marker, given the origin and the ordered anchors, in this plane governed by integer steps and endless reflections. The answer must emerge as whole numbers, elegantly summarizing a complex dance of points into a pair of coordinates, fulfilling the Academy’s stringent demands and earning you a place among the revered masters of spatial arcana.

This is the Midnight Radio Broadcast Archive, where cryptic transmissions from the digital abyss unfold each night. Tonight, we delve into the peculiar kingdom of Strings, a mysterious realm ruled by the constant shift of characters—a place where sequences, made purely of ten secret digits, dance endlessly under the moonlight. In this kingdom, a curious phenomenon exists: a pattern is called “good” if circling the sequence left or right leads to identical outcomes, a perfect symmetry in motion.

In the laws of this bizarre land, imagine a string as a circle of friends holding hands—each friend represented by a single digit. A **left swirl** of this circle means the friend at the front steps aside, and the entire circle twists so that the second friend takes the lead, pushing the first to the rear. Meanwhile, a **right swirl** has the friend at the tail sprint to the front, shifting the entire circle so that what was at the end now commands the gaze of the realm. Only when these two motions create the same new arrangement is the circle declared harmonious, or "good." But here’s the twist: the original circle might be too unruly, refusing to fall into such magic with ease.

Tonight’s challenge broadcasted across the invisible waves is this: given several sequences—each a chain of digits between zero and nine—you are entrusted with the task of determining how to best prune these circles. Your goal is to cut away the least number of friends from the sequence so that the remaining ring becomes good, perfectly balanced under both left and right swirls. The constraints of this spectral world constrain you—no sequence is ever shorter than a pair of digits, and no storyline exceeds hundreds of thousands in length. Your duty is to find the minimal number of removals for each sequence, ensuring the ultimate symmetry with minimal sacrifice.

The code of reception requires you to first receive an integer heralding how many sequences are to be examined. Then, on every following line, you receive one digit-filled sequence—a coded message from realms beyond. After deciphering, your reply will be concise: a single integer for each sequence, whispered back, revealing the minimal cuts needed to restore balance. Remember, your mission is to cause the least disruption, preserving as much of the original pattern as possible while achieving that elusive goodness.

Listen closely as the archive relays an example of distortions and restorations: first, the digits “95831” enter the ether. To attain harmony, three friends vanish, leaving only a pair who mirror each other perfectly under swirls. Next, the string “100120013” demands a harsher pruning—five must go, leaving a circle of zeroes that twinkle in symmetric splendor. Finally, “252525252525” arrives already pure; no excisions needed, the circle already spins perfectly in both directions—an effortless badge of goodness.

As midnight fades, the archive closes this transmission: your craft is to listen to these sequences, discern the minimal trims necessary, and cast back your answers—a quiet march towards restoring order in the eternal dance of digits.

In the mystical realm of Eldranthia, every aspiring monster tamer studies the ancient art of Creature Fusion, where combining two compatible monsters results in a stronger, more formidable being. Legend tells of the simplest fusion, called the "Unity Bond," where two creatures merge effortlessly, their energies combining in the purest way possible. While this fusion seems straightforward, even the mightiest tamers sometimes falter during its execution, as subtle nuances in the creatures’ essences challenge even the most basic attempts.

Within the Grand Academy of Eldranthian Tamers, trainers receive their challenges written in the ancient scrolls. Each scroll contains two sacred numbers, representing the unique energy levels of two creatures ready to unite. These numbers never exceed the scale of a thousand, reflecting the capped power of beginner monsters. The creatures’ energies are always presented on a single line of the scroll, separated only by a gentle space, as if to symbolize the thin thread connecting them.

The tamer’s task is deceptively simple: to meld these two worthies, capturing the fully combined vigor of their bond without loss or distortion. The fusion must manifest as a single number— the total combined magical strength of the pair—revealed clearly on its own scroll line. Success means showing the grand sum of their powers, demonstrating the essence of unity in its purest numeric glory.

For example, when a tamer opens a scroll inscribed with energies “5” and “14” penned side by side, the mage’s spirit must produce the true measure of their fusion: nineteen. In a grander test, two creatures possessing energies of three hundred eighty-one and four hundred ninety-two come together, and the tamer reveals eight hundred seventy-three, the perfect numeric echo of their unity.

Thus, the ancient ritual tests not just knowledge but precision; the champions of Eldranthia prove their mastery by taking the delicate energies shown on one scroll line and presenting the flawless sum on the next. Only then do they earn the title of Master Fusionist, forever honored in the scrolls of Eldranthia. Will you accept this challenge, and bring forth the true might hidden within simple bonds?

In the shadowed alcoves of the ancient Enchanted Library, a revered tome of witch’s alchemy whispered of a mystical conundrum. Deep within its yellowed pages lay the quest of the Triple Essence, where three rare essences — Aether, Bloom, and Cinder — must be blended under strict cosmic laws. The alchemist’s guild measured these essences not just by their quantity but by the delicate balance woven when they mingled. Each essence must be drawn in strictly positive amounts, never zero or less, for only then would the brew hold its power.

The laws of the cosmos, however, dictated two binding rules for any concoction’s potency. First, the combined pairwise mingling of essences—the bond formed by Aether with Bloom, Aether with Cinder, and Bloom with Cinder—must produce a resonance less than or equal to a great celestial threshold. This subtle energy is likened to the sum of each product of two different essence amounts. Second, the total sum of the three essences poured into the cauldron must not eclipse a chosen limit, a boundary set by the alchemist’s physical resources or ritual capacity. These constraints ensured the harmony of the potion and preserved the natural order of alchemical balance.

The challenge to the aspiring witches was straightforward yet profound: for many such thresholds of resonance and total capacity, count all possible ordered trios of essence quantities that obey these cosmic edicts. Every unique ordering of essence proportions summoned a different spell binding; thus, (one cup of Aether, two cups of Bloom, one cup of Cinder) was distinct from (two cups of Aether, one of Bloom, one of Cinder). The quest was to enumerate all valid triads where each essence was present in at least one measure, and both the sum of pairwise products and the sum of all three amounts remained within their prescribed bounds.

Witches recorded their inquiries in scrolls. The first scroll recorded the number of inquiries, from as few as a single incantation to as many as ten thousand. Each line after featured two enchanted numbers: one declared the maximum allowed mingling resonance, and the other the maximum overall essence total for a particular trial. These numbers never spanned beyond the reach of a million to preserve the arcane balance in scaling spells. The covenant of the tome guaranteed that the aggregated resonance and total essence sums of all these inquiries would never overload the mystical ledger beyond that million-measure threshold.

To unveil wisdom from the tome’s enigmatic runes, witches delivered their response as a single number for each query: the count of every possible ordered triple of positive essences that could abide the celestial laws imposed. The tome itself shed light on some answers: when the resonance was seven and the total essence limit stood at four, only four triads sufficed, including the humble (1,1,1), and its permutations where one essence grew to two cups while the others held firm at one. For a more demanding resonance and sum, like ten and five respectively, the count swelled to ten, as richer combinations emerged from the cosmic shadows.

Thus, the ancient alchemists continue their dance of numbers, tirelessly penning down each triad, seeking all possible essence blends that balance the dance of powers. In weaving these felt boundaries into tangible counts, they transform the raw chaos of the universe into formulas and spells, unlocking the purest secrets hidden in the intricate ballet of three entwined essences.

In the forgotten recesses of a desolate amusement park, legend spoke of the grandest jackpot hidden beneath layers of time and dust. The park’s mischievous spirit, Sparkle, agreed to reveal portions of this treasure—but only under a tense countdown. Treasure seekers found themselves limited not by gold, but by moments: every move they made could add to their score, but the chance to act would vanish like a ghost when Sparkle’s final countdown triggered a catastrophic end.

Here, the treasure was organized as two long rows of mysterious gleaming plates, each exactly the same length. One row held the “initial values,” vibrant and full of potential fortunes. The other row contained “decay values,” like the fading echoes of past enchantments, always ready to drain a slice of glory from the plates when they were touched. A seeker’s operation was simple yet challenging: choose one plate, add its current value to your total score, then weaken that plate by reducing its fortune by an amount equal to the plate's fading strength—never letting it drop below nothingness. Time was finite; the park’s magic allowed only a fixed number of touches before it would erupt in ruin. The quest was to maximize the riches gathered within those limited chances.

The challenge, therefore, was to journey through several trials—each trial presenting unique sets of plates and magic decay. For each trial, the seeker would know precisely how many plates there were, and how many operations, or touches, were allowed before destruction. They were given the initial values of each plate, shining brilliantly, and the decay values that whispered how their glow would dim after each contact. With this knowledge, they had to cleverly plan the order and choice of every touch to secure the highest possible accumulation of treasure before the inevitable explosion.

In the chronicles of this park, the seeker's ledger must follow a strict ritual: it starts by recording the number of trials they intend to attempt. Then, for every trial, the ledger notes down the number of plates and the permitted number of touches. On the next page appear the initial fortunes of the plates in a neat row, followed closely by the shimmer-dims, the decay values. After the seeker’s calculation, the ledger must proudly display one final number for each trial: the greatest score achieved by touching the plates within the allotted operations.

Recall a seeker attempting five trials of fortune: the first trial with three plates and four touches resulted in a score of twenty-one; the second, with a larger set and nine touches, climbed to three hundred forty-nine. The third trial boasted a thousand touches, achieving twenty-seven; while the fourth, making a million touches on a single plate, amassed a staggering 500,000,500,000 points. The final trial, a complex dance through ten plates and six touches, culminated in a score of forty-seven. These scores stand as testament to cunning strategy and seizing fleeting fortunes amid fading light. The abandoned park waits silently, daring the next seeker to test their wit against Sparkle’s cruel ticking clock.

In the bustling city of Lanternia, every year during the grand Lantern Festival, the city’s districts are illuminated by a network of glowing lanterns connected by radiant silk ropes. Each district is represented by a glowing orb, and between them stretch the silk ropes, forming an intricate, branching canopy of light—there are no loops, only paths connecting one district to another, much like tree branches reaching out. Tonight, the city elders wish to prepare the canopy for a special ritual: they plan to sever some of these ropes, but only in such a way that all remaining clusters of connected lanterns have an even number of orbs, symbolizing harmony and balance.

The rules of the festival canopy are strict. The city consists of a certain number of these glowing orbs, at least one and as many as one hundred thousand—a vast expanse of connected light. For most orbs, exactly one silk rope links them to another, ensuring that the entire canopy is a giant, sprawling tree with exactly one less rope than the total number of orbs. The elders carefully note down the silk rope connections, with each one uniting two distinct orbs, crafting the complete festival tree. Because the canopy is structured as a tree, there are never any circular paths or repeating loops—each lantern is reachable without crossing a previously lit path.

Now, the elders’ challenge: they seek to sever as many silk ropes as possible, but with a crucial condition—each distinct cluster of glowing orbs left afterward must number exactly even in their count. No cluster may be left with an odd number of orbs, for that would disrupt the sacred balance. Sometimes, this task is impossible; if no matter how many ropes are cut the city cannot be divided this way, the elders must accept the failure and mark it accordingly.

The festival logkeeper records the grand task: first, a number revealing just how many lantern orbs form the canopy that year. Then, below that, each successive line tells which two orbs are connected by a silk rope. Once the elders enact their plan, the log finally shows the number of ropes cut, achieving the maximum elegant division where all clusters glow with even numbers—or a sorrowful mark showing such division was unattainable.

To illuminate the challenge with past experiences, the log recalls a small canopy of four orbs connected as follows: orb two to orb four, orb four to orb one, and orb three to orb one. There, by severing a single rope between orb one and orb four, two beautifully balanced clusters of two orbs each remain, marking a successful cut of one rope. Conversely, a canopy of three orbs linked from orb one to orb two and orb one to orb three defies the ritual’s even harmony; no cuts yield all even clusters, so the log laments with a mark indicating failure. A larger tapestry of ten orbs, with connections carefully woven in lines such as from orb seven to orb one, and orb eight to orb four and ten, among others, finds a solution with four elegant cuts, maximizing the desired balance. On the smallest scale, a mere pair of orbs connected by a single rope can only remain as is, with no cuts taken—yet the balance is naturally perfect.

Thus, the Lantern Festival continues, with each year’s canopy meticulously recorded: the sacred number of orbs, the silk ropes that connect them, and the grand number of cuts made or the absence thereof, guiding Lanternia in its radiant quest for balanced light.

In the sprawling cosmic menagerie of the Nebulon Sector, the Alien Zookeepers maintain a fascinating line of containment corridors, each corridor stretching from one coordinate in space to another. These corridors never share edges exactly aligned; no two endpoints of these passageways ever perfectly overlap, preserving the sanctity of each path’s start and end. The grand challenge set before the Alien Zookeepers is to understand the hierarchical relationships between these corridors based on their stretches through space.

According to the ancient zoning conventions of the Nebulon containment protocols, each corridor is defined by its cosmic start point and its cosmic endpoint, with the start always hovering at a smaller spatial number than the endpoint. Each corridor floats along this cosmic line, stretching vast or minute distances but never touching the exact boundary where another corridor begins or ends. A corridor is said to contain another corridor if the latter lies completely inside its starting and ending cosmic coordinates, never poking beyond those cosmic bounds.

The peculiar task bestowed upon the Alien Zookeepers is to survey a given number of these corridors — possibly hundreds of thousands, as many as two hundred thousand and five hundred more pathways — each with fantastical start and end points anywhere between the far reaches of negative one billion and positive one billion. Their job is to enumerate, for every single corridor, precisely how many other corridors it contains within its cosmic stretch. The task is not simply to acknowledge containment but to count all such internal corridors exhaustively, ensuring maximum efficiency and comprehensiveness in cataloging these cosmic nesting layers.

The input given to each Zookeeper begins with a single line revealing the total count of corridors under observation — a number as vast as two hundred thousand and five hundred in the busiest sectors. Following this, each of the next lines unveils two numbers: the cosmic beginning and the cosmic end of each corridor, always ensuring the beginning is less than the end and no two corridors share an endpoint. After such knowledge is faithfully ingested, the Zookeeper must produce one line per corridor, declaring the integer count of how many other corridors lie completely inside it — no guesswork, no partial containment, just clear, absolute nesting tallies.

To illuminate this cosmic conundrum, consider first a quartet of corridors stretching from their starts to ends: one reaching from one to eight, one modestly from two to three, another between four and seven, and a final from five to six. Here, the mighty corridor from one to eight contains three others nested within: the two-to-three corridor, the four-to-seven corridor, and the five-to-six corridor. The corridor from two to three contains none, as no smaller passage lies fully inside. The four-to-seven corridor contains just one—the five-to-six corridor while the five-to-six corridor stands alone without any within. Outputting these counts, the Zookeeper writes three on the first line, followed by zero, one, and zero on the lines after.

In a second scenario, with three corridors stretching from three to four, from one to five, and from two to six, the contemplation differs. The corridor from three to four contains none, being the smallest single stretch itself, whereas both the one-to-five and two-to-six corridors each contain one other corridor nestled entirely inside their respective cosmic bounds, yielding an output of zero for the smallest and one for each of the larger, overlapping corridors. Thus, through this meticulous assessment, the Alien Zookeepers ensure the cosmic order of containment remains clear and unchallenged throughout their vast lineup of containment corridors.

In the bustling metropolis of Festivia, renowned for its grand celebrations, the Entertainment Event Flow Designers are the unsung heroes who orchestrate the energetic choreography of the Festival Coins. These precious tokens aren't just currency—they represent the essence of joy, motion, and excitement, crafted meticulously from the legendary Five Triangles of Merriment. Each triangle-shaped coin has a unique value engraved upon it, rising in harmony like a festival crescendo: the smallest spark holds the value of a single joyous step, the next pulses with the energy of a trio’s dance, followed by the sixfold rhythmic beats of a drum circle, then the tenfold symphony of a grand parade, culminating in the majestic fifteen-firework spectacle. The city never doubts that any desired amount of Festival Spirit can be composed from these tokens, for their flow is as endless as the festival itself.

Within the sacred halls of Event Design, a strict yet elegant rule governs the creation of Festival Coin sets to bring to life the Festival Sequence: given a grand target spirit score, the Designers must summon the fewest possible Festival Coins whose combined harmony equals exactly that level of festive vigor. To maintain the fluidity and efficiency of the celebrations, there are many such target scores announced by the Festival Council—each one calling for a new energetic configuration. The Designers take this as a challenge not just to meet the exact level of spirit, but to do so with the graceful economy of motion, never overwhelming the festival floor with unnecessary twirls or beats.

When the Festival Council sends forth their decrees, the rhythm-keepers receive the number of inquiries—the count of distinct Festivity Challenges to resolve. For each of these, they receive one number representing the exact spirit intensity required for the upcoming spectacle. Taking each in turn, the Designers must unveil the minimal ensemble of Festival Coins summoning precisely that spirit: no more, no less, and crafted from the abundant treasury of those five special triangular tokens. Their success is measured not by a surplus of sparkle, but by the elegant simplicity of their design—the fewest number of these tokens decking the stage, ensuring the festival’s pulse remains steady and true.

Consider a series of festival commands: the first calls for a spirit of just one—the smallest spark, summonable by a single one-step coin alone, thus the Designers jubilantly present one coin. When asked for a spirit of two, the dance becomes more intricate, requiring the pairing of two one-step sparks in sequence. For a spirit of three, the Designers summon a single trio-dance coin, a marvel of efficiency. A call for a spirit of five invites a combination of two one-step sparks alongside the trio's dance, together summing to the perfect harmony of five steps. As these challenges continue, the Designers weave combinations from the triangle coins—sometimes doubling six-step drum beats to reach high spirits with minimal effort, or blending the largest fireworks with the smaller sparks to compose captivating displays.

When the time comes to report their artistry, the Designers issue their answers line by line, one for each festival challenge: the number of coins forming that enchanting blend of spirit intensity. For example, the grand spirit of ninety-eight demands eight coins, masterfully combined. The more colossal spirit scores—such as hundreds of millions—find themselves answered with millions of coins, each carefully counted to ensure perfect harmony without waste or excess. The festival thrives on such precision, where every token is a step, every step a beat, and every beat a pulse in the city's joyous heart.

Thus, the Festival Coin designers continue, their work a blend of art and logic, always seeking minimal ensembles to meet their festival’s grand spirit calls. For each festival challenge announced, they respond with the smallest chorus of coins that capture exactly the requested spirit, ensuring the city’s celebrations flow endlessly, brilliantly, and with the perfect rhythmic grace.

In the heart of a bustling village, there stood a quaint tea house known far and wide for its intricate system of tea service. The tea house was inspired by a scholar’s codex written in a language of letters and shadows, where the arrangement of delicate tea leaves on plates resembled a string of ancient runes. This string was made entirely of humble lowercase letters, carefully laid out in a linear sequence no longer than five thousand characters, each whispering a secret of flavor and tradition.

The tea house operated under a unique tradition. The master brewer was tasked with identifying all pairs of tea leaves arranged on these plates such that the selection—from the first chosen leaf to the last—contained, somewhere in order but not necessarily consecutively, a special pattern symbolizing the revered word "bear." This pattern was like a sacred chant requiring an uninterrupted sequence of four particular leaves in the exact order: the leaf symbolized by a brush stroke akin to 'b,' followed by ones akin to 'e,' 'a,' and 'r.' These sequences could start from any position in the chosen range, but the order and immediacy of these four symbols were sacred and unbreakable.

The challenge for the tea house manager was as follows: given the single line of tea leaves arranged across the table, the manager had to count all possible selection pairs—starting from one leaf and extending to the same or any further leaf—that included at least one sacred chant spelled out perfectly somewhere within their span. The goal was not simply to find such a selection but to tally all possible pairs where the chant arises, ensuring the grandness of the tea ceremony was fully appreciated and recorded.

When a visitor handed over their request, they presented the line of leaves as a string of letters, one on a single line, reflecting the entire spread. The answer expected was a solitary number printed on a separate line: the total sum of all valid pairs of leaves that bore the sacred chant within their range. Efficiency and completeness were key, for the ritual’s purity depended on counting every offering that contained the chant, respecting the length and sequence limitations of the original string.

Consider the case of a string like "bearbtear." The master found that the first leaf pairing starting with 'b' and ending with 'r' (through various extensions) contained the chant exactly six times, a testament to the chant’s frequent occurrence near the start of the sequence. In a grander example, "bearaabearc," the leaves wrapped in their ancient song twenty times, perhaps echoing the multiple secret charms camouflaged within longer sequences.

Thus, the tea house’s rich tradition was preserved by counting these sacred occurrences, ensuring every selection sung the ancient chant of the bear, guiding the visitors’ experience as they sipped in harmony with the mysteries held within the string of leaves.

In the quiet, dimly lit halls of the ancient city museum, every night, the vigilant night guard compiles a detailed report that unveils hidden patterns within the exhibits. Tonight, the guard faces a unique challenge guarding a gallery filled with mysterious numbered artifacts, each glowing softly with their own secret energy. There are many such artifacts lined up in a sequence, no fewer than one and no more than three hundred thousand— a vast collection. Each artifact hums with a power that never falls below zero and never soars beyond a billion, a range revered in this dim domain.

The museum’s lore explains that each pair of start and end artifacts in the sequence conjures a special quantity—a secret signal derived from their combined energies. This mystical signal is calculated by performing a cryptic ritual known only to the guardians: blending their individual powers through a magical "bitwise XOR" process, a combination that balances their energies to reveal a hidden truth. The strength of this truth is then magnified by the length of the artifact chain it came from—that is, how many artifacts lie between and including the chosen start and end. The guardians must discover the sum of all these magnified truths for every artifact pair in this lengthy assembly.

Tasked with this sacred duty, the ancient night guard must listen to input from the curator’s scroll: first, the total number of glowing artifacts in the display, written plainly on the first line. On the very next line, the exact mysterious energies of these artifacts are shared, listed one by one like stars in the night. The guard’s mission is to reveal a single number—the aggregate of all these layered truths, once tempered by the sacred modulus of 998244353, which protects the number from becoming unwieldy and keeps the magic stable.

To illustrate, consider the smallest gallery of three sparkling artifacts. The energies standing as one, three, and two unlock secrets when combined and summed according to the ancient ritual. Each pair (and single artifact) sends out a whispered truth: for example, the first artifact alone reveals one, the duo of the first and second becomes twice two, and the trio of all three artifacts returns thrice zero, continuing through every possible cluster. When they are all combined, the night guard’s final reckoning is twelve—a perfect blend of energies and lengths. In a more complex gallery of four, with energies like 39, 68, 31, and 80, the truths accumulate to a grand total of 1337 by the museum’s arcane calculation. And in the most intricate gallery housing seven mighty artifacts, the answer unfolds as a magnificent 257421502.

Thus, each night the guard reads the energies, stretches across every possible cluster of artifacts, performs the sacred ritual of revelation, and returns the ultimate score to be recorded. This score, forever protected within the modulus, captures the illuminated spirit of the gallery and honors the ancient museum’s timeless tradition.

In a distant world known for its intricate postal maze, there existed a legendary postcard known simply as The Number. This postcard bore a grand number imprinted upon it — a mighty value that could tower higher than ten billion suns in their fiery glory. The destiny of this postcard was tied to an ancient algorithm performed by the Keepers of the Maze, who sought to unravel its essence through a ritual called the Prime Subtraction.

The Prime Subtraction followed a strict code of conduct. First, the Keepers would gaze upon the postcard’s grand number. Should it be reduced entirely to nothing, the ritual was complete. If not, they would then summon the smallest possible messenger prime, a prime that divides the number flawlessly — a rare and disciplined envoy in the prime council. Upon locating this smallest prime envoy, the Keepers would gently subtract its influence from the grand number, thereby reducing the card’s power. This ceremony would repeat each time, seeking the smallest prime emissary anew, until the grand number was stripped to zero, marking the ritual complete.

Your noble task, as an aspiring Keeper, is to predict how many such prime envoy subtractions will be required to bring the grand number down to silence. You will be presented with the grand number inscribed on a single sacred line, representing the postcard’s might — a number assured to be no less than two, yet never surpassing the staggering size of ten billion times ten thousand. Your goal is to determine the count of subtractions needed until the number becomes null, signaling the ritual’s end.

To recount an early example: when the grand postcard number was a modest five, the smallest prime envoy was simply five itself. One solitary subtraction brought the number gracefully down to zero, ending the ritual in a single stroke. In another tale, when the number stood as a humble four, the smallest prime was the loyal two. It was summoned swiftly, subtracted twice — first from four to two, then from two to zero, thereby requiring two subtractions to conclude the process.

Thus, the ritual’s outcome is a single number inscribed as the final tally — the total times the Keepers had to call upon their prime envoys to pare down the grand postcard number to nothingness. With this knowledge, the Keepers continue their eternal quest to master the Prime Subtraction and unveil the secrets of the grand postcard numbers they encounter across the sprawling maze.

In the vibrant world of Retro Toy Catalogs, there existed a legendary collection cherished by all — the Lucky Digit Series. This collection showcased toy office doors adorned with special lucky numbers made entirely of the two iconic digits, the Magnetic Seven and the Glowing Eight. These digits were revered because, when combined, they whispered enchantment into any room they marked. The magical city, ITopolis, was designing its grand new Toy Tax Tower, where every office needed its own unique lucky number on a door-plate to bring good fortune and prosperity.

The Toy Tax Tower’s master designer faced a curious challenge: each door-plate could display only a limited number of speaking digits, determined by a maximum length that no license visor would dare exceed. Let this maximal length be no smaller than a single digit and no longer than fifty-five digits strung in a row. The license rules decreed that every lucky number must be crafted strictly from the two sacred digits — the Magnetic Seven and the Glowing Eight — never mixing in other figures. Each office demanded its exclusive charm, so no two doors could share the same lucky numbers. The designer’s quest was to discover just how many office doors could be outfitted with these sacred lucky numbers without breaking the rules or running out of magical digit space.

The master’s task was clear: given the maximum allowed number of digits that the door-plates could bear, determine the grandest possible count of unique, pure lucky numbers — those beautifully formed only by sevens and eights — that fit into any office door number within this limit. This meant counting every blessed number from the smallest single-digit charm up to the mightiest number with the full allowed digits on the plate. The final number, glowing with possibility, represented the total offices that could be enchanted and officially counted.

To navigate this delicate combinatorial dance, the master cataloger accepted a single wisdom token, represented simply by one whole number on the first line of the ancient scroll — the maximum digit length for the door-plates. The master would then reveal a single enchanted tally: the maximum count of unique lucky numbers, all crafted from sevens and eights, whose digit lengths did not surpass the given limit. This tally would empower the Toy Tax Tower planners with the knowledge to allocate their offices correctly and efficiently.

For example, when the magic limit of digits was set at two, the ledgers show six possible lucky numbers: the singular seven and eight, plus every two-digit duo of these digits: seventy-seven, seventy-eight, eighty-seven, and eighty-eight. Thus, six doors could uniquely sparkle with their lucky numbers in the tower. This count rose exponentially as more digits were permitted, weaving a tapestry of lucky numbers expanding across the office floors, ensuring no two shared the same charm.

With this understanding, the master was ready to inscribe new sections of the catalog — taking the single digit-limit token as input and producing the maximum count of lucky door-numbers for countless new Toy Tax Towers waiting to prosper within ITopolis.

In the grand citadel of IT City, where innovation spun as finely as the hands of crafted clockworks, a distinguished guild sought to assemble new coteries of inventors. As recorded carefully in the Clockmaker’s Routine Notebook, this guild required each guild circle to be formed of a suitable number of adept artisans — no fewer than five, but never more than seven — each chosen for their unique flair and skill. Their whims, bound by tradition rather than mere chance, dictated every circle be neither too small to spark invention nor too large to stifle harmony.

One dawn, the guild sent word across the city streets and glass towers, beckoning all artisans who bore resumes of skill and promise. Soon, packets arrived from exactly a certain number of potential brethren, each packet a testament to a hopeful’s readiness. The Record of Arrivals noted this number to be no less than seven, and no more than seven hundred seventy-seven; these were the bounds of gathering, representing a delicate balance between opportunity and order.

Within the careful tedium of the guild’s archives, the task was to enumerate every possible way to compose a circle from those who had mentored their talents to join the guild’s grand designs. They would measure each distinct circle — a unique gathering of artisans, chosen without repetition — containing either five, six, or seven members. Each arrangement symbolized a potential future forged in collaboration, and the desire was not merely to find one such possibility, but to uncover the full spectrum of these harmonious alliances. This tally would reveal the breadth of options for the guild’s master strategists to contemplate.

The input to the guild’s calculation was a single number—the count of all hopeful artisans who had sent signals of interest. This number was noted plainly on a parchment, representing the total pool of candidates from which circles might be formed. The output, then, was a solitary count—a number reflecting all the distinct circles that could be spun together, sized to the guild’s exacting standards. This number was sought to be as precise and comprehensive as the gears of the finest clock.

For instance, when precisely seven artisans had come forth, the guild calculated twenty-nine unique circles — a tapestry of five-, six-, and seven-member groups, interwoven like the stops and struts of a delicate mechanism. The Record thus preserved this result as a guiding light for future assemblies.

In sum, the guild’s chronicles held both the command and the answer: given the total number of hopeful artisans arriving at the city’s gates, determine how many unique circles of five, six, or seven artisans could be crafted. By doing so, the guild ensured that innovation would not only begin, but flourish, its possibilities counted and cherished as carefully as every tick and tock in a clockmaker’s routine.

In the vast simulation console of the Endless Ecosystem, there exists a sprawling network of interconnected habitats, each numbered from the first to the final in a great sequence. These habitats are linked by migration corridors, where creatures can traverse from one to another. Each corridor carries a certain travel challenge, measured by the energy cost the creatures must expend to cross it. The entire ecosystem is alive with complex pathways—some corridors connect the same habitat at both ends, some habitats may be connected by multiple distinct corridors, making the network rich and intricate.

The guardians of this ecosystem seek to understand the easiest journey a creature can take to travel from the very first habitat in the sequence to the ultimate habitat at the end. To do so, they must consider the number of habitats within the network, which can be enormous—anywhere from a modest pair to over a hundred thousand, and the same goes for the corridors weaving between them, which might be nonexistent or as many as the creatures can imagine, up to a hundred thousand as well. Each corridor has a known difficulty level, a positive value indicating the energy a creature must spend to traverse it, which may range up to over a million units. These corridors form a living web, inclusive of loops that start and end in the same habitat and multiple corridors between the same two habitats, adding complexity to the paths.

The quest is as follows: given the total habitats and their connecting corridors, the wise ecosystem observer must chart the path from the initial habitat to the final one that demands the least total energy from the traveler. If no journey is possible across the web, the verdict is a despairing announcement of impossibility. But if the journey exists, the observer must reveal a sequence of habitats representing the path, from the first habitat in the sequence to the last, which altogether form the lightest toll possible. When many such paths exist with the minimum toll, any one of them suffices, for the creatures care only to conserve their strength optimally.

The observer receives the ecosystem’s details in a structured manner: on the first line of the report, a pair of numbers declares how many habitats exist and how many corridors link them. Following this, each corridor is described on a separate line by naming the two endpoints it connects and the energy cost required to traverse. The corridors’ descriptions allow the observer to reconstruct the entire migratory web. Once the traveler’s lightest path is determined, the observer must output either a line containing a single symbol indicating no path exists, or else print the ordered sequence of habitats along the minimal-energy route — beginning with the starting habitat and ending with the final one. The observer's message, therefore, might be as brief as a solitary negative sign or as detailed as a full stepwise itinerary.

Consider this scenario: five habitats are connected by six corridors. One example of the paths is a corridor from habitat one to two demanding two energy units, another from two to five costing five, and so on. In such a rich network, the lightest migration path might pass through habitats one, then four, followed by three, and finally five, combining corridors in a way that the total toll is minimal. The observers would narrate this sequence in their report. If the corridors shrink or vanish, and no passage from the first to the last is possible, the observer’s output is simply the universal symbol of impossibility. Through such structured observation, the Endless Ecosystem’s migratory routes reveal their most efficient secrets.

In the vibrant city of Paradera, an ancient Festival Parade was held annually, where dancers lined up in a grand queue to showcase their moves. Each dancer carried a special badge adorned with a sequence of symbols—these symbols, unique to each, represented the dancer’s identity in the festival. The entire sequence was known as the Grand Sequence, containing a multitude of dancers, sometimes as vast as one hundred thousand or more, each proud and distinct.

Within Paradera’s traditions, the council introduced a mystical ritual to categorize dancers by the number of 'sparkles' on their badges, counted through a secret method. This method began with considering an invisible number known as zero sparkles for none. When the count involved doubling—a dancer’s badge number multiplied by two—the sparkle count remained unchanged, reflecting the council’s belief that doubling did not add new sparkles. However, when the badge number was an odd figure, created by doubling and then adding one, the sparkle count increased by exactly one more sparkle, symbolizing the extra vibrance brought by oddness. Through this system, the council could tell how sparkly each dancer’s badge truly appeared.

The parade master now puzzles over a widespread question: among all dancers arranged in the queue, how many pairs share the exact same sparkle count? The rule is that dancers standing earlier in the line always have their first lawfully recognized position, strictly before those later in the sequence. The bright quest is to count all such pairs where both dancers sparkle identically—not just any, but as fully and as efficiently as possible in the grand lineup, revealing the hidden connections knitted by the council’s sparkle logic.

When the festival’s call is heard, the parade master asks the crowd to reveal the total number of dancers in the procession on the first signal. On the very next line, the crowd must proclaim each dancer’s badge number, each a positive symbol from the smallest to nearly a billion, spaced clearly as if marching in rhythm; each badge number reverberates the sparkles they carry. With this information, the master will deliver a single, grand answer on one shining line—the total count of these special matching pairs, fulfilling the council’s riddle and painting the festival with unity.

To live through an example: if three dancers step forth carrying badges marked 1, 2, and 4, every possible pair bubbles with matching sparkle counts, resulting in three shining pairs. Yet, when three different badges hold numbers 5, 3, and 1, only one special pair truly shares the same sparkle melody, the first two dancers. Thus, in the grand festival of Paradera, counting the sparkle-matched pairs is not just a task, but a celebration of hidden harmony amidst dazzling uniqueness.

In the quiet halls of Willowbrook High, Rash found himself intrigued by a mysterious sequence of lockers lined perfectly along the school corridor. Each locker was either painted a deep midnight black or a bright snowy white, arranged in a linear fashion that stretched across the entire wing. The total number of lockers, which he called the corridor’s length, varied with each new hallway he explored but never grew beyond an impressively long chain, sometimes numbering in the hundreds of thousands.

In this school, there was an old puzzle whispered among students: finding special sections of these lockers where a curious pattern repeated itself, not just twice but thrice, evenly spaced apart. More specifically, Rash learned that a special set of lockers must satisfy a hidden school rule. For any chosen continuous stretch along the corridor—from some locker position to another farther down the line—there should be a trio of lockers where each locker’s color matches perfectly, and these three must line up at equal intervals inside that stretch. In other words, starting at a certain locker inside that section, if you count a certain equal number of lockers to find the second and then the third, all three lockers must be the exact same color. What mattered was that the first locker’s position, the spacing between the lockers, and the last locker’s position all snugly fit within the defined section Rash was observing.

Rash wanted to know how many such special sections there were in any given corridor. His challenge was to take one long sequence of locker colors—not longer than a few hundreds of thousands—and scan through all possible continuous parts of it. He needed to identify every segment where at least one such perfect triplet pattern could be found, no matter where it appeared or how far apart the repeated lockers were, so long as the spacing was consistent and all three were the same color. That meant counting all pairs indicating the start and end lockers of these sections, from the first locker to the last, and everything in between, that revealed this magical repetition.

The student handbook explained how to present the data for this task. Rash would read the corridor’s locker colors as a sequence of blacks and whites, recorded simply as zeros and ones, all in one single line. From this record, he was to output a single number—the count of all continuous sections that housed this special repeating pattern. It was a number that would show just how many hidden pockets of these triple matches lay within the corridor’s grand stretch of lockers.

For instance, when Rash examined a corridor where the lockers alternated colors like black, white, black, white, black, white, he found that only three unique stretches revealed the hidden triple pattern—one stretching from the very first to the very last locker, another starting from the second locker to the last, and one more stretching from the first locker to just before the end. Yet, in a corridor painted with blocks of two black lockers followed by two white lockers, repeated twice more, none of the stretches revealed such magic. The count was zero, leaving the corridor free of the mysterious triple patterns.

In this way, Rash’s daily diary of corridors and their secret codes grew richer, as he carefully marked, for each sequence of lockers, how many hidden treasures the school’s color mystery contained.

**Survival Log: The Quest for Vital Sparks**

In the endless wasteland of a shattered world, remnants of humanity cling to survival amid the ruins. Among the scattered survivors, one group relies on an ancient artifact known as the Spark Array—a chain of vital energy nodes that pulse with hidden power. This chain is formed by a sequence of nodes, each labeled with a unique number marking its place from the ashes of history. For any mission, the team receives two numbers carved into stone—the starting spark and the ending spark—defining a continuous chain of nodes, numbered from the first up to the last without gaps.

The rules of this world dictate a harsh law: the collective power preserved by these nodes can only ignite if there exists a shared ember, a persistent bit of energy present in every active node simultaneously. If, by the binding forces of the array, the shared ember fades to nothing—meaning no shared spark persists—the entire chain fails to light. To salvage the situation, the survivors must sever some nodes from this chain, removing as few as possible, until the remaining sparks share at least one unbroken ember feeding their strength. Keeping nodes comes at a price though; the group strives to retain as many as possible for maximum collective power, so the goal is to trim the chain just enough to rekindle that vital common spark.

Each mission begins with a report detailing the number of trials they must face, listing one mission per line. For every mission, the ledger logs two numbers—the first node's mark and the last node's mark—between which the team must evaluate the chain. From there, the team must report, for each mission, the smallest number of nodes that must be jettisoned from this sequence to guarantee that all remaining nodes share a glowing ember—none of these embers can vanish in the shadow of their neighbors. If the very chain as given already shares this ember fully, their answer will be zero, signaling no sacrifice is needed.

Consider the following logs retrieved from past trials: One mission’s chain starts at ember one and stretches to ember two. At first glance, their combined glimmer seems weak, fading to nothing when bound; a single node cast away—either the first or the second—leaves a surviving node burning bright alone, restoring the vital spark. Another mission spans from ember two to ember eight. Here, the chain is longer and the sparks delicate. The team finds that by discarding three chosen nodes—specifically those at places four, five, and eight—a cluster of embered nodes remains, all sharing a radiant ember undiminished. The records also tell of a shorter chain from ember four to five standing strong without any removal, glowing uniformly. Yet another mission from ember one to five demands two cuts—sacrificing two nodes to achieve the shared glow. Lastly, a formidable chain stretching from one hundred thousand to two hundred thousand embers requires a substantial removal of over thirty thousand nodes just to cling to a common spark.

These chronicles guide the survivors, teaching them that to maintain the harmony of the Spark Array, it is not enough to merely exist; each member must share the same vital ember, a truth critical to surviving the cold void of their fractured world. Through judicious severing and preservation, they keep the flame alive, one ember at a time.
